Abstract

1 Introduction

This paper formalizes the Pattern Masking for Dictionary Matching (PMDM) problem: Given a dictionary ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D} of dğ‘‘d strings, each of length â„“â„“\ell, a query string qğ‘q of length â„“â„“\ell, and a positive integer zğ‘§z, PMDM asks to compute a smallest set KâŠ†{1,â€¦,â„“}ğ¾1â€¦â„“K\subseteq\{1,\ldots,\ell\}, so that if qâ€‹[i]ğ‘delimited-[]ğ‘–q[i], for all iâˆˆKğ‘–ğ¾i\in K, is replaced by a wildcard, qğ‘q matches at least zğ‘§z strings from ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D}. Equivalently, PMDM asks to minimize the union Kğ¾K of mismatching positions between qğ‘q and strings from ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D} to obtain at least zğ‘§z matches after replacing the positions in Kğ¾K with wildcards.

Let us start with a true incident to illustrate the essence of the PMDM problem. In the Netherlands, water companies bill the non-drinking and drinking water separately. The 6th author of this paper had direct debit for the former but not for the latter. When he tried to set up the direct debit for the latter, he received the following message by the company:

â¬‡
Is this you?
Initial: S. Name: P****s E-mail address: s******13@g***l.com
Bank account number: NL10RABO********11.

The rationale of the data masking is: the client should be able to identify themselves but not infer the identity of any other client. Thus, the masked version of the data should conceal as few symbols as possible (set Kğ¾K) but correspond to a sufficient number (zğ‘§z) of other clients.

In fact, the PMDM problem lies at the heart of two important applications, featured in large-scale real-world systems: (I) Record linkage of databases containing personal dataÂ [58, 42, 43, 55, 60], and (II) Query term droppingÂ [10, 30, 45, 57].

Record linkage is the task of identifying records that refer to the same entities across databases, in situations where no entity identifiers are available in these databasesÂ [23, 33, 50]. This task is of high importance in various application domains featuring personal data, ranging from the health sector and social science research, to national statistics and crime and fraud detectionÂ [23, 38]. In a typical setting, the task is to link two databases that contain names or other attributes, known collectively as quasi-identifiers (QIDs)Â [59]. The similarity between each pair of records (a record from one of the databases and a record from the other) is calculated with respect to their values in QIDs, and then all compared record pairs are classified into matches (the pair is assumed to refer to the same person), non-matches (the two records in the pair are assumed to refer to different people), and potential matches (no decision about whether the pair is a match or non-match can be made)Â [23, 33]. Unfortunately, potential matches happen quite oftenÂ [11]. A common approachÂ [58, 55] to deal with potential matches is to conduct a manual clerical review, where a domain expert looks at the attribute values in record pairs and then makes a manual match or non-match decision. At the same time, to comply with policies and legislation, one needs to prevent domain experts from inferring the identity of the people represented in the manually assessed record pairsÂ [55]. The challenge is to achieve desired data protection/utility guarantees; i.e., enabling a domain expert to make good decisions without inferring peoplesâ€™ identities.

To address this challenge, we can solve PMDM twice, for a potential match (q1,q2)subscriptğ‘1subscriptğ‘2(q_{1},q_{2}). The first time we use as input the query string q1subscriptğ‘1q_{1} and a reference dictionary (database) ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D} containing personal records from a sufficiently large population (typically, much larger than the databases to be linked). The second time, we use as input q2subscriptğ‘2q_{2} instead of q1subscriptğ‘1q_{1}. Since each masked qğ‘q derived by solving PMDM matches at least zğ‘§z records in ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D}, the domain expert would need to distinguish between at least zğ‘§z individuals in ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D} to be able to infer the identity of the individual corresponding to the masked string. The underlying assumption is that ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D} contains one record per individual. Also, some wildcards from one masked string can be superimposed on another to ensure that the expert does not gain more knowledge from stitching the two strings together, and the resulting strings would still match at least zğ‘§z records in ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D}. Offering such privacy is desirable in real record linkage systems where sensitive databases containing personal data are being linkedÂ [43, 60]. On the other hand, since each masked qğ‘q contains the minimum number of wildcards, the domain expert is still able to use the masked qğ‘q to meaningfully classify a record pair as a match or as a non-match. Offering such utility is again desirable in record linkage systemsÂ [55]. Record linkage is an important application for our techniques, because no existing approach can provide privacy and utility guarantees when releasing linkage results to domain expertsÂ [44]. In particular, existing approachesÂ [43, 44] recognize the need to offer privacy by preventing the domain expert from distinguishing between a small number of individuals, but provide no algorithm for offering such privacy, let alone an algorithm offering utility guarantees as we do.

Query term dropping is an information retrieval task that seeks to drop keywords (terms) from a query, so that the remaining keywords retrieve a sufficiently large number of documents. This task is performed by search engines, such as GoogleÂ [10], and by e-commerce platforms such as e-BayÂ [45], to improve a userâ€™s experienceÂ [30, 57] by making sufficiently many search results available to them. We can perform query dropping by solving PMDM on a dictionary of strings corresponding to document terms, and a query string, corresponding to a userâ€™s query. Then, we provide the user with the masked query, after removing all wildcards, and with its matching strings from the dictionary. Query term dropping is an important application for our techniques, because existing techniquesÂ [57] do not minimize the number of dropped terms. Rather, they drop keywords randomly, which may unnecessarily shorten the query, or drop keywords based on custom rules, which is not sufficiently generic to deal with all queries. More generally, our techniques can be applied to drop terms from any top-zğ‘§z database queryÂ [35], to ensure there are zğ‘§z results in the query answer.

4 Approximation Algorithm for PMDM

Clearly, PMDM is at least as hard as PMDM-Size because it also outputs the positions of the wildcards (set Kğ¾K). Thus, PMDM is also NP-hard. We show existence of a polynomial-time approximation algorithm for PMDM whose approximation factor is given with respect to dğ‘‘d. The authors ofÂ [22] show a polynomial-time ğ’ªâ€‹(d1/4+Ïµ)ğ’ªsuperscriptğ‘‘14italic-Ïµ\mathcal{O}(d^{1/4+\epsilon})-approximation algorithm, for any constant Ïµ>0italic-Ïµ0\epsilon>0, for the Minimum Union (MU) problem. In AppendixÂ C, we show a polynomial-time reduction from PMDM to MU that implies the following result.

Theorem 4.1.

For any constant Ïµ>0italic-Ïµ0\epsilon>0, there is a polynomial-time ğ’ªâ€‹(d1/4+Ïµ)ğ’ªsuperscriptğ‘‘14italic-Ïµ\mathcal{O}(d^{1/4+\epsilon})-approximation algorithm for PMDM.

Applying TheoremÂ 4.1 to solve PMDM is not practical, as in real-world applications, such as those in Introduction, dğ‘‘d is typically in the order of thousands or millionsÂ [24, 28, 30, 57].

A hypergraph Hğ»H is a pair (V,E)ğ‘‰ğ¸(V,E), where Vğ‘‰V is the set of nodes of Hğ»H and Eğ¸E is a set of non-empty subsets of Vğ‘‰V, called hyperedges â€“ in order to simplify terminology we will simply call them edges. 8 Summary of Greedy Heuristic for PMDM and Experiments

We design a greedy heuristic for PMDM which, for a given constant Ï„â‰¥1ğœ1\tau\geq 1, applies TheoremÂ 6.1 iteratively, for some kâ‰¤Ï„ğ‘˜ğœk\leq\tau. In iteration i=1ğ‘–1i=1, we apply TheoremÂ 6.1 for k=1,â€¦,Ï„ğ‘˜1â€¦ğœk=1,\ldots,\tau and check whether there are at least zğ‘§z strings from ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D} that can be matched when at most kğ‘˜k wildcards are substituted in the query string qğ‘q. If at least zğ‘§z such strings exist, we return the minimum such kğ‘˜k and terminate. Clearly, by TheoremÂ 6.12, the returned solution K1subscriptğ¾1K_{1} is an optimal solution to PMDM. Otherwise, we proceed into the next iteration i=2ğ‘–2i=2. In this iteration, we construct string qK1=qâŠ—K1subscriptğ‘subscriptğ¾1tensor-productğ‘subscriptğ¾1q_{K_{1}}=q\otimes K_{1} and apply TheoremÂ 6.1, for k=1,â€¦,Ï„ğ‘˜1â€¦ğœk=1,\ldots,\tau, to qK1subscriptğ‘subscriptğ¾1q_{K_{1}}. This returns a solution K2subscriptğ¾2K_{2} telling us whether there are at least zğ‘§z strings from ğ’Ÿğ’Ÿ\mathcal{D} that can be matched with qK2=qK1âŠ—K2subscriptğ‘subscriptğ¾2tensor-productsubscriptğ‘subscriptğ¾1subscriptğ¾2q_{K_{2}}=q_{K_{1}}\otimes K_{2}. If there exist such strings, we return K1âˆªK2subscriptğ¾1subscriptğ¾2K_{1}\cup K_{2} and terminate. Otherwise, we proceed into iteration i=3ğ‘–3i=3, which is analogous to iteration i=2ğ‘–2i=2. The time complexity of the heuristic is ğ’ªâ€‹((N+NÏ„/3)â€‹â„“)ğ’ªğ‘superscriptğ‘ğœ3â„“\mathcal{O}((N+N^{\tau/3})\ell) and the space complexity is ğ’ªâ€‹(N)ğ’ªğ‘\mathcal{O}(N). A complete description of the heuristic can be found in Appendix D.

An extensive experimental evaluation demonstrating the effectiveness and efficiency of the proposed heuristic on real datasets used in record linkage, as well as on synthetic datasets, is presented in AppendixÂ E. In the experiments that we have performed, the proposed heuristic: (I) produced nearly-optimal solutions for varying values of zğ‘§z and â„“â„“\ell, even when applied with a small Ï„ğœ\tau; and (II) scaled as predicted by the complexity analysis, requiring fewer than 333 seconds for d=6â‹…106ğ‘‘â‹…6superscript106d=6\cdot 10^{6} in all tested cases. These results suggest that our methods can inspire solutions in large-scale real-world systems, where no algorithms for PMDM exist.

Proof of TheoremÂ 4.1.

The reduction in TheoremÂ C.2 implies that there is a polynomial-time approximation algorithm for PMDM. Sanity Check.

TheoremÂ 3.1 (reduction from kğ‘˜k-Clique to kğ‘˜k-PMDM) and TheoremÂ 4.1 (approximation algorithm for PMDM) do not contradict the inapproximability results for the maximum clique problem (see Appendix B), since our reduction from kğ‘˜k-Clique to kğ‘˜k-PMDM cannot be adapted to a reduction from maximum clique to PMDM-Size.

Two-Way Reduction.

The reader can probably share the intuition that the opposite to the reduction of TheoremÂ C.2 is easy to prove. We give this proof next for completeness.

Theorem C.4.

MU can be reduced to PMDM in polynomial time.

Efficiency.

Having shown that GR produced nearly-optimal solutions, we now show that it is comparable in terms of efficiency or faster than BA for synthetic data. (BF was at least two orders of magnitude slower than the other methods on average and thus we omit its results.) The results for NCVR were qualitatively similar (omitted).
